QUESTION 1

Investigate the relationship between the number of cylinders () and highway fuel efficiency. Look at the variables, and decide which type of plot (scatterplot, line plot, boxplot, or bar chart) best summarizes their relationship.

ggplot(mpg) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x=as.factor(cyl),y=hwy))

According to the graph, as the number of cylinders increases, the average highway miles per gallon decreases. For instance, cars with 4 cylinders have a median of around 28 highway miles per gallon, while cars with 8 cylinders have a median of approximately 16 highway miles per gallon.

QUESTION 2

The gapminder dataset is a very rich dataset containing data on life expectancy and GDP per capita of most nations in the post-WW2 period. You can load it by loading the gapminder library.

Part 1

To begin, simply plot the relationship between GDP per capita and life expectancy.

ggplot(gapminder) +
  geom_point(aes(x=gdpPercap,y=lifeExp))

The graph shows that most countries had a low GDP per capita post-WW2. Also, there does not seem to be a linear relationship betweenGDP per capita and life expectancy although some countries with relatively higher GDP per capita (around the 30000 value) seem to have a higher life expectancy (around 70-80 years).

Part 2

We see some odd outliers here. Plot the country names. Which nations are the outliers?

ggplot(gapminder) +
  geom_text(aes(x=gdpPercap,y=lifeExp, label = country))

The clear outlier is Kuwait. I would conclude that Kuwait’s GDP per capita varied significantly, in comparison to other countries, after WW2. Also, I would say that Kuwait has had GDP per capita values greater that other countries.

Part 3

Building on your original plot, show each continent in a separate color, and also add a smoother for each continent.

ggplot(gapminder, aes(x=gdpPercap,y=lifeExp, color = continent)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

From the plot, Asia has a trend on the relationship between GDP per capita and Life Expectancy that extends beyond that of others, as we have seen this is due to Kuwait being an outlier. This trend also happens to reach a maximum Life Expectancy point around the 45000 GDP per capita mark and then go down the higher the GDP is. This is surprising because one would expect the Life Expectancy to be high the higher the GDP per capita, yet this suggests otherwise, at least in Asia.

Other continents, the Americas, Europe and Oceania, have a moderate trend where there are no significant outliers and the trends go up suggesting a positive relationship between GDP per capita and Life Expectancy.

However, African countries show to not surpass the 30000 GDP per capita mark, with a smoother that begins going up and then falls back down.

Part 4

Now look at the evolution of life expectancy over time, by country, using a line plot.

ggplot(gapminder) +
  geom_line(aes(x=year,y=lifeExp, group = country))

Although it is hard to interpret the individual plots due to the number of countries, I can still see that in general, the line plots show a trend of life expectancy that goes upwards over time for most countries.

Part 5

The graph above is quite hard to read. Facet by continent.

ggplot(gapminder) +
  geom_line(aes(x=year,y=lifeExp, group = country)) +
  facet_wrap(~ continent, nrow=2)

After faceting by continents, I can see an upward trend in life expectancy over time in the Americas, Europe, Oceania, and Asia. However, in Africa I can see some countries’ trends go down towards the end. Also, Asia has some countries that fluctuate more significantly in comparison those of other continents.

QUESTION 3

The Palmer Penguins data set is another fun R data set. It contains data on 3 types of penguins that can be found on the Palmer archipelago in Antarctica: chinstrap, gentoo, and adelie. These data were collected from 2007 - 2009 by Dr. Kristen Gorman with the Palmer Station Long Term Ecological Research Program, part of the US Long Term Ecological Research Network.

Part 1

Make a bar chart of the number of penguins per island, and note the species of penguins on each one. What patterns do you observe?

ggplot(data=penguins) +
  geom_bar(aes(x=island, fill = as.factor(species)), position = 'dodge')

Firstly, the island with most penguins is Biscoe, followed by Dream, and lastly Torgersen. Interestingly, the Adelie species is present on each island, yet, on Biscoe and Dream, Adelie penguins are the second most common species. The data shows that the Gentoo species is only present on Biscoe, while Chinstrap is only present on Dream island.

Part 2

Examine the relationship between flipper length and body mass, by species.

ggplot(data=penguins, aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g, color = species)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Overall, for all three species, I find a relatively positive trend between flipper length and body mass, which makes sense because you would expect a larger and heavier penguin to have a longer flipper. Also, the Gentoo penguins seem to be the biggest species between the three, given their body mass and flipper length.

Part 3

What do you find once you separate out the data by sex?

ggplot(data=penguins, aes(x=flipper_length_mm, y=body_mass_g)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()+
  facet_wrap(~ sex)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

I find that for both male and female penguins, there is also a relatively positive trend between flipper length and body mass, yet, we can see the data points being slightly higher in both body mass and flipper length for male penguins. Moreover, there are some penguins whose sex were not identifiable, thus the NA values.

Part 4

Examine the relationship between bill length and depth. First, pool across all species, and give a linear summary of the effect. What do you observe? What happens once you split by species?

ggplot(data=penguins) +
  geom_smooth(method="lm", aes(x=bill_depth_mm, y=bill_length_mm)) +
  geom_point(aes(x=bill_depth_mm, y=bill_length_mm))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

The plot shows that bill depth and length have a negative linear relationship, in other words, the deeper the bill, the shorter it is.

ggplot(data=penguins) +
  geom_smooth(method="lm", aes(x=bill_depth_mm, y=bill_length_mm)) +
  geom_point(aes(x=bill_depth_mm, y=bill_length_mm)) +
  facet_wrap(~ species)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

However, when we separate the data by species, we can see a positive relationship between bill length and depth in all species. This could be an example of Simpson’s paradox.
